"All of this will take time so we won't have time to work today. Sorry!"
What is happening here?
The Monkey doesn't seem like someone you want at the wheel.
He lives entirely in the present moment.
He has no memory of the past, no knowledge of the future, and he is only interested in two things: ease and fun.
In the animal world, it works correctly.
If you are a dog and spend your life doing only easy and fun things, you are fantastic!
For the Monkey, humans are just another animal species.
You had to sleep, eat, and create a new generation. This could work in prehistoric times.
But if you haven't noticed, we don't live in prehistoric times.
We live in an advanced civilization, and the Monkey doesn't know what that is.
That's why we have another person in our brain, the Rational Decision Maker, who gives us the ability to do things that no other animal can do.
One can project themselves into the future.
One can have an overview of the situation.
One can make long-term plans.
And he wants to take all of this into account.
And he wants us to do just what is logical, here and now.
Sometimes it makes sense to do easy and fun things, like when you have dinner or go to bed or enjoy some well-deserved free time.
There is an overlap. Sometimes they agree.
But on other occasions, it is much more logical to do more difficult and less enjoyable things, in the interest of the situation as a whole.
A conflict is then created.
For the procrastinator, this conflict tends to end in the same way every time, leaving them spending a lot of time in this orange zone, an easy and fun place, completely outside the Circle of Logic.
I call it the Dark Playground.
The Dark Playground is a place that all procrastinators know very well.
It's the place where we engage in leisure activities at times when they should not take place.
The fun you have on the Dark Playground is not actually fun, as it is undeserved and the air is filled with guilt, fear, anxiety, self-disgust, all these feelings of a good procrastinator.
In this situation, with the Monkey at the wheel, the question is: how can the procrastinator get to the blue zone, a less enjoyable place, but where the really important things get done?
It turns out that the procrastinator has a guardian angel. Someone who always watches over them in their worst moments. Someone called the Panic Monster.
The Panic Monster sleeps most of the time, but wakes up suddenly every time a deadline approaches too closely or there is a risk of public embarrassment, a career disaster, or any other terrible consequence.
And most importantly, it's the only thing the Monkey is afraid of.
It became very relevant in my life very recently, when the people from TED contacted me six months ago and invited me to give a presentation.
